give us that there is a positive integer ''s'' such that 

&lt;math> \displaystyle 
\begin{align}
x &amp;= 3 + 6s.
\end{align}
&lt;/math>

Substituting into the second equation yields

&lt;math> \displaystyle 
\begin{align}
3 + 6s &amp;\equiv 1 \mod{10}.
\end{align}
&lt;/math>

Isolating for 0 gives

&lt;math> \displaystyle 
\begin{align}
2(3s +1)&amp;\equiv 0 \mod{10}.
\end{align}
&lt;/math>

Hence, we have that 5 must divide the term in the bracket, that is

&lt;math> \displaystyle 
\begin{align}
3s+1 \equiv 0 \mod{5}
\end{align}
&lt;/math>

This gives 

&lt;math> \displaystyle 
\begin{align}
3s &amp;\equiv -1 \mod{5}.
\end{align}
&lt;/math>

Multiplying both sides by 2 gives

&lt;math> \displaystyle 
\begin{align}
s &amp;\equiv -2 \equiv 3 \mod{5}.
\end{align}
&lt;/math>

Hence &lt;math> \displaystyle s = 3 + 5t&lt;/math> for some integer ''t''. Thus, 

&lt;math> \displaystyle 
\begin{align}
x &amp;= 3 + 6s = 3 + 6(3 + 5t) = 3 + 18 + 30t = 21 + 30t
\end{align}
&lt;/math>

and hence all solutions are given by

&lt;math> \displaystyle x \equiv 21 \mod{30}&lt;/math>.

statement_latex:
Determine all integers \emph{x} that satisfy the following system of
linear congruences.

\begin{align*}
x &\equiv 3 \mod{6}\\
x &\equiv 1 \mod{10}
\end{align*}

